<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
The specific epithet alludes to the Spider monkeys, or ateles (
<taxonomicName class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Ateles" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ateles panisczis" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="panisczis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Ateles panisczis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), locally called kwata, who consume the fruits of this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Sabatier, D" journalOrPublisher="Missouri Botanical Garden Press" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" publicationUrl="https://sciencepress.mnhn.fr/sites/default/files/articles/pdf/a1997n2a8.pdf" refId="B63" refString="Sabatier, D, 1997. Description et biologie d'une nouvelle espece de Virola (Myristicaceae) de Guyane. Adansonia ser. 3 19(2): 273-278. https://sciencepress.mnhn.fr/sites/default/files/articles/pdf/a1997n2a8.pdf" title="Description et biologie d'une nouvelle espece de Virola (Myristicaceae) de Guyane. Adansonia ser. 3 19 (2): 273 - 278." url="https://sciencepress.mnhn.fr/sites/default/files/articles/pdf/a1997n2a8.pdf" year="1997">Sabatier 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myristicaceae" genus="Virola" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Virola kwatae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="species" species="kwatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Virola kwatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was previously known from French Guiana. However, in a recent study of herbarium specimens at New York Botanical Garden, a collection with fruit made in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Amapá">Amapa</normalizedToken>
state, Brazil was located. To our knowledge this represents the first record of this species among the Flora of Brazil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
